<DOC><DOCNO> AP881216-0243 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 0825EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Belgium-InterestRate     12-16 0253</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Belgium-Interest Rate,0262</SECOND><HEAD>Belgium Raising All Banking Rates Second Time In Week</HEAD><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Belgium's central bank announced onFriday that it was raising the country's key interest rates for thesecond time in less than a week.   The Belgian National Bank said the discount and lombard rateswould be increased by 0.25 of a percentage point each to respectiverates of 7.75 percent and 8 percent.   The bank also announced that it was increasing the three-monthTreasury bill rate by a quarter point to 7.65 percent. Thethree-month rate is considered to be the most important in Belgianbanking.   In addition, the bank is raising the one-month Treasury bill rateto 7.5 percent from 7.35 percent and the two-month rate to 7.5percent from 7.4 percent.   The increase in the treasury bill rates takes effect immediately,while the hike in the discount and lombard rates takes effect onMonday. The lombard rate is that charged for short-term borrowingsfrom the central bank using securities as collateral, and thediscount rate is the interest charged commercial banks for loans.   The Belgian move follows the half point increase in WestGermany's Lombard rate to 5.5 percent, announced on Thursday.   This is the second time this week that Belgium has increased keyinterest rates amid signs of a general rise in interest ratesworldwide.   On Wednesday the bank announced that it was increasing thediscount and lombard rates by a quarter point each and raised thethree-month rate by a similar margin.</TEXT></DOC>